    public class Processing
extends javax.swing.JFrame
    Processing is a Application Programming Interface for Processing Coding Language to function in Java IDE, It is Designed to implement Processing Running Environment into Java.
    (Programmed Referring to Processing version: 3+)

    Class Processing enables most Processing Codes to Run in Java Environment. It is an SubClass of JFrame. All Methods and Functions within JProcessing Are Programmed According to the Processing IDE and Offer Identical Functionality. The full Documentation on all Processing Methods are on the Processing IDE Official Website (links down below).

    Note: This Class runs as A Processing Code Library that Allows Processing Codes to Run directly in Java Environment with minimal Modifications. Please Refer to the Included Template to see how you can Implement it into your Java Codes. Note: The Default Encoded Character Set used in JProcessing is "GB18030", not "UTF-8". You can use Processing.charset = "Name_of_the_Charset" To change the Global Default Charset for JProcessing

    Known Issue: Always call loadPixels() before Accessing pixels[] Array is Strictly Required, otherwise NullPointerException will be Thrown. (This was not Mandatory in Processing IDE)

    Known Issue: PImage.resize() will Not Change the Size of the specified Image directly. Instead, the Resized Image will be in the Return value. The Correct way to Resize is yourImage = imageToResize.resize(x,y)

    Detail: The Return Type of requestImage() is Future<PImage>, not PImage.

    Detail: Theoretically, External Libraries Designed for Processing IDE should also Work with JProcessing after Manually Download and Include them in your Java Project. However, this is largely Untested. The Sound Library ddf.minim is Tested to Work.

    Important: Unlike Processing IDE, Every Event Method in JProcessing including setup() and draw() has protected Access Privilege. Refer to the Format Listed Below when Overriding them.

    Todo: Processing Functions like: P3D Graphics, Table, Array Functions, XML, PDF, Noise, PShape etc. are Not yet Available.
    Todo: Further Testing on Processing Libraries are Required to ensure their Compatibility

      • Processing

        public Processing()
        Construct a new GUI window of JProcessing

        After JProcessing has been constructed and initialized, a new thread will be started, in which setup() is called after 100ms of delay. Then, a timer will be started to invoke draw() at the frequency of the targeted frameRate.

        As the secondary thread sleeping, the original thread will start to initialize variables defined inside the subclass of JProcessing.

        Throws:
        java.awt.HeadlessException - if GraphicsEnvironment.isHeadless() returns true

    • Method Detail

      • setup

        protected void setup()
        Processing void setup() function, invoked after JProcessing being initialized.

        setup() will be invoked only once at 100ms after the initialization of new JProcessing, before the draw() is invoked. Data loading, variable initialization, and environmental property definition should be done in setup().

        Under normal circumstances, setup() should not be manually invoked again after its initial execution.

        See Also:
        <void setup()> in Processing IDE

      • draw

        protected void draw()
        Processing void draw() function, invoked before the update of every frame.

        draw() will be invoked repeatedly at the frequency up to the GUI's frame rate specified by frameRate(rate). if the task in draw() takes too long to finish, the frame rate will be lowered to the rate of completion of draw() in each second.

        Only Functions that need to run at every frame should be put inside draw(), such as graphics rendering, image displaying, mouse or key input detecting etc. Time consuming tasks such as image loading should not be done in draw(), otherwise will lower the frame rate dramatically. Instead, they should done in setup() or asynchronously in another thread.

        If a new frame is needed to be updated manually, use redraw() to render a single frame. It is very uncommon to find situations where draw() needs to be executed without the actual update of contents on the screen. In that case, draw() can be invoked manually but it will not be thread safe. In that case, it is recommended to add synchronized modifier when overriding draw().

        See Also:

      • redraw

        public void redraw()
        Processing redraw() function, execute the code within draw() one time and then manually update a frame.

        This should only be used when the automatic frame update is disabled by noloop(), otherwise it will have no effect. Upon calling, the draw() method will be immediately invoked, then a new frame will be rendered after the completion of any previous ongoing render task.

        Do not call this method within draw(), otherwise the program will run into infinite loops.

        See Also:
        <redraw()> in Processing IDE

      • linspace

        public static <value extends java.lang.Number> float[] linspace(value start,
                                                                value end)
        Generate linearly spaced row vector represented by a float array.

        By default, this method will return a array of 100 evenly spaced value between x1 and x2. This is the same as calling linspace(start, end, 100).

        Type Parameters:
        value - any type of number
        Parameters:
        start - the start value x1
        end - the end value x2
        Returns:
        a row vector in float[] of 100 evenly spaced values between x1 and x2.

      • linspace

        public static <value extends java.lang.Number> float[] linspace(value start,
                                                                value end,
                                                                int n)
        Generate linearly spaced row vector represented by a float array.

        Type Parameters:
        value - any type of number
        Parameters:
        start - the start value x1
        end - the end value x2
        n - number of points to generate
        Returns:
        a row vector in float[] of n evenly spaced values between x1 and x2.
